# Desktop mode invariants

The desktop launcher (`cursor_view/desktop/`) runs the same Flask app
that terminal mode serves, but inside a native pywebview window pointed
at a random loopback port. The invariants below are the ones that are
easy to regress because they straddle the Python launcher, the embedded
webview, and the React app.

## Wait before navigating

`cursor_view/desktop/__init__.py::run_desktop` must **never** point the
window at `http://127.0.0.1:{port}/` as the `create_window(url=...)`
initial URL. The Werkzeug server runs on a daemon thread that is not
guaranteed to be accepting connections by the time pywebview navigates,
so an eager navigation flashes the embedded webview's native "site
can't be reached" frame on cold launches.

The required shape, owned by `run_desktop`:

- Create the window on the inline splash from
  `cursor_view/desktop/splash.py::splash_html()`, passed as
  `webview.create_window(html=...)`, never on the loopback URL.
- Pass a worker function to `webview.start(func, ...)` that calls
  `cursor_view/desktop/readiness.py::wait_for_server(port)` and only
  then calls `window.load_url(target_url)`. The probe runs on
  pywebview's worker thread so blocking on it cannot freeze the splash
  paint.
- A readiness timeout still navigates (best-effort) after a lazy `%s`
  warning, so the user is never stranded on the splash; the native
  startup-error dialog is a separate concern (Improvement 03).

Feed the splash as `html=`, **not** as an initial
`url="data:text/html;..."`. Chromium-based backends (notably WebView2
on Windows) block *top-level* navigation to `data:` URLs, so pywebview
resolves the payload as a relative path against the loopback origin and
the window 404s before the server is even up. The `html=` path routes
through each backend's native string-loader (WebView2
`NavigateToString`, WKWebView `loadHTMLString`, WebKitGTK `load_html`)
which has no such restriction. The same `html=`-not-`data:` rule
applies to every inline page the launcher shows, including the native
startup-error window in `cursor_view/desktop/error_window.py`.

## Startup errors go to a native window

Anything in `run_desktop` that can fail before the GUI loop starts
(`cleanup_orphan_temp_files`, `create_app`, `free_port`, `make_server`)
is wrapped in a single try/except that routes to
`cursor_view/desktop/error_window.py::show_startup_error` and exits
non-zero. `show_startup_error` runs its own `webview.start()` loop, so
it must only be called before the main `webview.start` — never from the
readiness worker. The readiness-timeout case (the main loop is already
running) instead loads `build_error_html(...)` into the existing splash
window via `window.load_html`. Both paths HTML-escape the message and
traceback (`html.escape`) before they reach the markup, so a failure
string containing `<` / `&` cannot break or inject into the page.

`wait_for_server` is stdlib-only (`urllib.request`), polls `GET /`
every 50ms with a 0.5s per-request timeout, returns `True` on the first
HTTP 200 and `False` on timeout, and stays silent on the first failed
attempt (connection-refused while the socket is still binding is the
expected cold-launch steady state). Do not swap it for `requests` or
add a heavier dependency — the stdlib-only discipline keeps the
PyInstaller bundle and its import-time cost lean, matching the
image-loading and export modules.

The splash markup is inline on purpose: it needs no disk read, ships
inside the PyInstaller bundle for free, and cannot 404 the way a
relative asset could before the server is up. Do not move it into
`cursor_view/export/vendor/` — that directory is reserved for
HTML-export third-party assets per
[`project-layout.mdc`](project-layout.mdc).

## Single-instance lockfile

Desktop mode is single-instance. `cursor_view/desktop/single_instance.py`
owns a `desktop.lock` JSON file (`{pid, port, started_at_ns}`) in
`cursor_view_cache_dir()`, next to `webview-storage/`. `run_desktop`
calls `acquire_lock(port)` after binding the listening socket: on a
live-holder collision it `notify_existing(port)`s the running instance
(loopback `POST /__desktop_focus__`, which calls
`webview.windows[0].show()/restore()`), closes its own socket with
`server.server_close()` (not `server.shutdown()`, which deadlocks before
`serve_forever` runs), and exits 0. The lock is released in the
`finally` via `release_lock()`, which only deletes the file when the
recorded PID is still ours.

Staleness is PID-liveness, and the liveness probe is platform-split for
a load-bearing reason: **never call `os.kill(pid, 0)` on Windows.**
CPython implements `os.kill` on Windows via
`OpenProcess` + `TerminateProcess(handle, sig)`, so a signal-0 "probe"
would kill the target (including the test process). POSIX uses
`os.kill(pid, 0)`; Windows opens the process with
`PROCESS_QUERY_LIMITED_INFORMATION` through `ctypes` and checks
`GetExitCodeProcess == STILL_ACTIVE` — a read-only existence check. The
focus route is registered only in desktop mode (via
`_register_focus_route` in `cursor_view/desktop/__init__.py`), never in
`cursor_view/routes.py`, so terminal mode stays free of webview
concerns. Regression-pinned by `tests/test_desktop_single_instance.py`
(including a direct `_process_alive(os.getpid())` assertion that doubles
as the Windows self-termination safety check).

## Native menu bar

The desktop window carries a File / Edit / View / Help menu built by
`cursor_view/desktop/menu.py::build_menu(api)` and passed to
`webview.start(menu=...)`. Two invariants keep it robust:

- **Route cross-mode actions through the bridge.** Every menu leaf that
  has cross-mode meaning calls a `cursor_view/desktop/api.py::DesktopApi`
  method rather than reimplementing the action: `Reload` →
  `reload_window`, `Quit` → `quit_app`, `View → Toggle Theme` →
  `toggle_theme`, `Help → Documentation` / `GitHub` →
  `open_url_in_browser`. The bridge is the single source of truth shared
  with terminal mode and the keyboard-shortcut path (Improvement 06), so
  the menu never owns logic the bridge should. Theme state in particular
  lives entirely in the React app — `toggle_theme` dispatches the
  `cursor-view:toggle-theme` `CustomEvent` (constant `EVENT_TOGGLE_THEME`
  in `api.py`, mirrored byte-for-byte by `DESKTOP_EVENT_TOGGLE_THEME` in
  `frontend/src/utils/desktopEvents.js`), which `useDesktopMenuEvents`
  (called once from `App.js::ThemeModeBridge`) turns back into the same
  `toggleDarkMode` the Header button drives. The clipboard **Edit** items
  (cut / copy / paste / select-all) are the deliberate exception: they
  are pure embedded-webview operations with no terminal-mode counterpart,
  so `menu.py::_run_edit_command` delegates them straight to the active
  window via `document.execCommand` instead of adding bridge surface. New
  menu bridge methods return the `{ok, error}` dict shape and must never
  raise across the JS boundary, matching `open_url_in_browser`. The
  `View → Toggle Developer Tools` item is appended only when the bridge
  was constructed with `debug=True` (`menu.py` reads the private
  `api._debug` directly so the flag stays out of pywebview's JS-exposed
  surface); `toggle_devtools` is best-effort because pywebview has no
  portable runtime devtools toggle.

- **No-menu fallback.** Not every backend renders `menu=`. WebKitGTK in
  particular silently ignores it, and a future stripped backend might not
  expose `webview.menu.Menu` at all. `run_desktop` gates construction
  behind `if hasattr(webview.menu, "Menu")` and falls back to an empty
  menu list with a single lazy `%s` `logger.info`, never an error — the
  app must launch fine with no menu. Because the menu is best-effort,
  every action it exposes must also be reachable another way (the Header
  button for theme, the right-click context menu for external links, the
  window controls for quit), so a backend that drops the menu never
  strands a user without the underlying capability. `build_menu` itself
  stays pure (constructs and returns the tree, no side effects) so
  importing `menu.py` never touches process state.

- **Menu accelerators are display-only; the frontend binds them.**
  pywebview's `webview.menu.MenuAction` takes only `(title, function)` —
  it has no shortcut/key parameter and no backend binds an accelerator
  from the menu. `menu.py::_with_accelerator` therefore appends the
  shortcut to the item *title* as a discoverability hint only
  (Cmd-glyph on macOS via `sys.platform == "darwin"`, `Ctrl+` prefix
  elsewhere). The real key handling lives in the frontend:
  `frontend/src/hooks/useGlobalKeyboardShortcuts.js` registers one
  global `keydown` listener, and `App.js` populates its `shortcuts` map
  **only in desktop mode** (Reload → `reload_window`, Quit → `quit_app`,
  Toggle Theme → `toggleDarkMode`) because the same combos collide with
  the browser's own in terminal mode. Clipboard edit keys
  (Cmd/Ctrl+C/X/V/A) are intentionally absent from that map so the
  embedded webview keeps handling them natively. The display format in
  `_with_accelerator` (Python) and `formatShortcut` (JS, in
  `frontend/src/utils/keyboardShortcuts.js`) must stay in sync, as must
  each displayed combo and its actual binding in `App.js`. The
  `Header.js` theme-toggle tooltip shows the `Ctrl/Cmd+T` hint only in
  desktop mode for the same reason the binding is desktop-only.

## Detecting desktop mode in React: render-time vs call-time

`frontend/src/utils/mode.js::isDesktopMode()` checks `!!window.pywebview`.
That is the right primitive for **call-time** gates — event handlers,
action callbacks, anywhere code runs in response to a user gesture — but
it is racy at **render/mount time** and must not be used there.

The race: pywebview's WebView2 backend on Windows injects
`window.pywebview` from its `NavigationCompleted` callback (see the
upstream `webview/platforms/edgechromium.py::on_navigation_completed` →
`webview/util.py::inject_pywebview`, which fires the `pywebviewready`
event only after injection). That runs **after** the React bundle has
executed and `App` has already mounted. A synchronous `isDesktopMode()`
inside a `useMemo` / `useEffect` / render body therefore returns `false`
on first render; pywebview's later injection triggers no React
re-render, so a memo whose only deps are unrelated state (e.g.
`[darkMode]`) stays stuck on its initial value forever. This is what
broke the keyboard-shortcut map in [`App.js`](../../frontend/src/App.js)
before the `useDesktopReady` migration: the shortcuts map resolved to
`{}` on cold launch, pywebview's later inject never re-fired the memo,
and Ctrl/Cmd+T / Cmd+R / Cmd+Q never matched anything.

Use [`useDesktopReady`](../../frontend/src/hooks/useDesktopReady.js) at
render/mount time. It seeds from the synchronous `isDesktopMode()`
check (so callers that mount *after* pywebview is ready render `true`
immediately) and then subscribes to the one-shot `pywebviewready`
event, flipping its returned boolean and forcing a re-render once the
bridge is live. Canonical consumers:

- `App.js::ThemeModeBridge` gates its `useMemo(shortcuts)` on
  `desktopReady` and lists it in the dep array, so the shortcut map
  installs the moment pywebview is injected.
- `Header.js` gates the `(Ctrl+T)` / `(⌘T)` tooltip hint on
  `desktopReady` so the hint appears on first paint of the post-inject
  render rather than only after some unrelated state changes.

`useDesktopMenuEvents` is the counter-example that confirms the
discipline: it installs its global window event listener
unconditionally (no mount-time gate at all) and the menu's Toggle Theme
worked correctly while the shortcuts were broken. That pattern is
viable when the listener has no per-mode setup cost and only matches
events that fire in desktop mode anyway. Anything that does have such a
cost (building a non-empty map, mounting a desktop-only component
subtree, choosing a desktop-only branch) must use `useDesktopReady`
instead.

## External links route through the bridge

External links (any `href` whose origin is not the loopback
`window.location.origin`) must never navigate the embedded webview or
spawn a second pywebview window — they go to the user's default browser
via `DesktopApi.open_url_in_browser` (which enforces the http/https
allowlist Python-side). Two surfaces share that single bridge method:

- The right-click "Open in Browser Tab" item in
  `frontend/src/components/AppContextMenu.js` (per-click, explicit).
- The global capture-phase interceptor in
  [`useDesktopExternalLinks`](../../frontend/src/hooks/useDesktopExternalLinks.js),
  called once from `App.js::ThemeModeBridge`, which transparently
  covers every `<a>` / `<area>` in the app (Header GitHub button, chat
  content links, image-lightbox "open in new tab") without changing
  their markup.

The interceptor is a call-time gate (`isDesktopMode()` inside the
handler, not at mount — so no `useDesktopReady` needed: by click time
pywebview is long since injected) and falls through to native behavior
when the bridge is not ready. It deliberately leaves three cases to the
platform: same-origin links (in-app react-router navigation), the
`download` attribute (a "save this file" affordance the bridge cannot
honor), and non-http/https schemes (`mailto:` / `tel:`, which the
bridge would reject anyway). It listens on both `click` and `auxclick`
and `preventDefault`s for left, middle, and modifier (Cmd/Ctrl/Shift)
clicks so every variant lands in the one OS browser tab; right-click
(`auxclick` button 2) is left to the context menu. Terminal/browser
mode is entirely unaffected because the handler no-ops outside desktop
mode, preserving native `<a>` behavior.

## Loopback-token auth in desktop mode

The random loopback port only deters drive-by scans; any local process
running as the same user can otherwise read every indexed chat off
`127.0.0.1:{port}`. [`cursor_view/desktop/auth.py`](../../cursor_view/desktop/auth.py)
closes that gap with a per-launch secret:

- `generate_token()` returns `secrets.token_urlsafe(32)`; `run_desktop`
  generates one token per launch, passes it to both `install_auth` and
  `DesktopApi(token=...)`, and it is never persisted.
- `install_auth(app, token)` registers a `before_request` that 401s any
  `/api/*` request whose `X-Cursor-View-Token` header **or**
  `cursor-view-token` cookie does not match (constant-time
  `hmac.compare_digest`). Non-`/api` paths (the SPA shell, static
  assets, `/__desktop_focus__`) and `OPTIONS` preflight are never
  gated — the shell must load so it can pick up the token, and the gate
  must not break CORS preflight.
- The same `install_auth` registers an `after_request` that sets the
  `cursor-view-token` cookie (`HttpOnly`, `SameSite=Strict`, not
  `Secure` because loopback is plain http) on the `text/html` SPA shell
  response, so non-axios same-origin requests (notably
  `<img src="/api/chat/.../image/...">`) carry the token automatically.
  This is an app-level hook, **not** a blueprint: a blueprint would have
  to shadow the catch-all `/` route in `cursor_view/routes.py` and risk
  an ambiguous mapping. `routes.py` stays free of desktop concerns.

Frontend: [`useDesktopAuth`](../../frontend/src/hooks/useDesktopAuth.js)
(called once from `App.js::ThemeModeBridge`, gated on `useDesktopReady`)
reads the token from the bridge's `get_token()` and sets it as the
default `X-Cursor-View-Token` axios header. The header and the cookie
are belt-and-suspenders: same-origin axios requests send the cookie
automatically too, so the brief window before the header is set still
authenticates. Exposing the token to the page via `get_token()` is safe
— the bridge is reachable only from inside our own webview, and the
token's job is to lock out *other* local processes that can read neither
the bridge nor the in-page value.

**Terminal mode never calls `install_auth`**, so browser mode is
unchanged and unauthenticated exactly as before. Regression-pinned by
[`tests/test_desktop_auth.py`](../../tests/test_desktop_auth.py)
(401 on missing/wrong header and cookie, 200 on correct header and
cookie, non-`/api` ungated, `OPTIONS` ungated, and the HTML-shell cookie
bootstrap with its `HttpOnly` / `SameSite` attributes).
